	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName> <date>Sept. 1. 1848</date>.</p>
				<p>Dr Sir.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I received your dated <date>Aug 14</date> &#38; now hasten to answer<lb/> it as I have in part <sic>attented</sic> to your commands.  <persName>Mr. Lerg</persName> states<lb/> that you promised <hi rend="underline">twelve</hi> numbers &#38; in as much as you reduced<lb/> it to <hi rend="underline">five</hi>&#44; the subscribers became disgusted &#38; were crying out<lb/> against it to him.  Not to be tormented by impertinent questions<lb/> he sent the box of undistributed numbers to my brother &#38;<lb/> they are now at my father&#39;s store awaiting your orders.<lb/>  I would do well to state something relative in the &#8220;Occident&#8221;<lb/> &#38; let me know what course to pursue.  The congregation<lb/> have as yet given me no answer&#44; as respects the Books.<lb/>  Father states <persName>Mr. Wright&#39;s</persName> account shall be <sic>attented</sic> to<lb/> &#38; he makes himself responsible.  <persName>Dr. Luzenburg&#39;s</persName> executor<lb/> acknowledges the accounts I shall shortly send in the<lb/> bill.  <persName>Mr. G. Jonas</persName> got a set of the Pentateuch but preferred<lb/> for use&#44; the sheep gilt at &#36;13 of which there were<lb/> two set&#44; farther took the other.  Let me know if <persName>Mr.<lb/> B. B. Hart</persName> has paid you.  There is about &#36;40 of yours<lb/> now in my hands counting the &#36;13 of <persName>Mr. Jonas</persName>.<lb/>  I think that you had better state in the &#39;Occident&#39;<lb/> also that the Books are for sale by me &#38; that will<lb/> save the advertisement &#38; have still the same effect.<lb/>  <persName>Mr. Marks</persName> will return me an answer soon.</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>I think <persName>Mrs Florance</persName> has already procured a set<lb/> as you state.  <persName>Mr. Newton</persName> will decline paying I<lb/> think he is at the <placeName>north</placeName> now&#44; that is for<lb/> those number he asked&#44; try &#38; see him yourself<lb/> while he is in <placeName>Phila.</placeName>  You gave me no answer<lb/> as to the disposal of that fine set of Prayer Books<lb/> at &#36;33.00&#44; does your silence approve or disapprove&#63;<lb/>  Acknowledge the receipt of <persName>Mr. Touro</persName> for vol IV.<lb/> <persName>J. Rodriguez</persName> for vol IV. <persName>Newton</persName> for IV &#38; V <persName>Sampson</persName> for<lb/> IV. V. &#38; VI. <persName>Philips</persName> IV &#38; V as I have collected said amounts.<lb/>  I shall shortly begin to correspond with you&#44; given<lb/> you a description of the progression of the Jews<lb/> in the city in relation to religious duties&#44; should<lb/> you think proper to allow them a place in the &#8220;Occident&#8221;<lb/> I shall be much obliged to you my signature<lb/> shall be &#39;Z&#39;.  The synagogue is fast <sic>progression</sic>&#44;<lb/> whose description shall be one of the themes<lb/> of my communications.  With this I think you are<lb/> sufficiently acquainted with your southern affairs.</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">&#38; I remain yrs.</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">Hen. S. Labatt</persName></p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p><addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
